Title = {Social media, criminal law, and legality},
Journal = {GRIFFITH LAW REVIEW},
Year = {2025},
Month = {2025 SEP 9},
Abstract = {This review examines Social Media, Criminal Law, and Legality by Laura
   Higson-Bliss, a timely and critical exploration of the intersection
   between criminal law and social media in addressing online misconduct.
   Drawing on Lon Fuller's framework of legality, the book highlights the
   limitations of existing legal norms in regulating digital behaviour
   without compromising core legal principles such as clarity,
   accessibility, and non-retroactivity. Structured in three main sections,
   the book first lays a theoretical foundation concerning freedom of
   expression and digital regulation, then evaluates the applicability of
   statutes like the Public Order Act 1986, Protection from Harassment Act
   1997, and the Online Safety Act 2023 to contemporary online offenses.
   The final section analyses platform accountability, offering comparative
   insights from France, Germany, and India. Higson-Bliss argues that
   criminal law interventions often lack precision, risk
   over-criminalisation, and disproportionately impact marginalised groups.
   The book advocates for a more holistic regulatory model that includes
   digital literacy and platform governance alongside legal reforms. While
   the review praises the book's analytical depth and comparative scope, it
   also notes the need for further discussion on the role of artificial
   intelligence in content moderation and broader engagement with legal
   developments beyond Western jurisdictions. Overall, this work provides
   essential insights for academics, policymakers, and legal practitioners
   working in the field of digital criminal law.},
